{{inline|date=August 2018}} [[Image:LavrentyevskayaLetopis.jpg|thumb|right|250px]] '''Laurentian Codex''' or Laurentian Chronicle ({{lang-ru|Лаврентьевский список, Лаврентьевская летопись}}) is a collection of chronicles that includes the oldest extant version of the ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' and its continuations, mostly relating the events in Northern Russia ([[Vladimir-Suzdal]]).
== The scribe and his source == The codex was not just copied by the [[Nizhny Novgorod|Nizhegorod]] monk Laurentius commissioned by [[Dionysius, Metropolitan of Kiev|Dionysius of Suzdil]] in 1377. The original text on events from 1284 to 1305 was a lost codex compiled for the Grand Duke [[Mikhail of Tver]] in 1305, but Laurentius re-edited the presentation of [[Yuri II of Vladimir|Yuri Vsevolodovich]], the founder of [[Nizhny Novgorod]], from positive into a negative, partly rehabilitating the role of Tatars. Vasily Komarovich studied traces of changes within the manuscript and established a hypothesis about differences between Laurentius' version and the lost one of the Tver chronicle.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Komarovič |first=Vasily L. |date=1976 |title=Из наблюдений над Лаврентьевской летописью [From oberservations of the Laurentian chronicle] |journal=Труды Отдела древне русской литературы Института русской литературы АН СССР Л. |volume=30 |pages=27–57 }} The critical edition ([[#CritEd|1926-1928]]) presented the text with all its variants given in other chronicles.</ref>
== Content == The Laurentian Codex compiled several codices of the Vladimir chronicles. It is the second edition of Nestor's chronicle, which had been already revised in 1116 by Sylvester, Hegumen of the St. Michael Monastery in the village of Vydubychi, under the reign of Prince [[Vladimir II Monomakh|Vladimir Monomakh]], and it is the oldest version known today. The codex is a unique source for the autobiographical chronicle called “Instruction of Vladimir Monomakh”.
The first part until folio 40 verso was written by an unknown scribe commissioned by [[Andrey Bogolyubsky|Andrew Bogolyubsky]]. In 1177 it was completed after the assassination of the prince. The second chronicle about [[Vsevolod the Big Nest]] continued up to 1193. The third which did glorify Vsevolod, was composed in 1212 by his son Yuri Vsevolodovich. The Vladimir Chronicles borrowed from sources of the Southern Rus', especially from [[Pereiaslav-Khmelnytskyi|Pereyaslavl Yuzhniy]], since Vladimir princes regarded the city as part of their patrimony.
The compilation referred to various periods until 1305, but the years 898–922, 1263–83 and 1288–94 had been omitted for reasons of censorship, and quite likely under supervision of Dionysios, Metropolitan of Kiev. The revision was done under great rush and another hand in the manuscript proves, that Laurentius' work was assisted by a second scribe whose hand can be found on the later added folios 157, 167, and on the verso side of folio 161.<ref>See the [http://expositions.nlr.ru/LaurentianCodex/_Project/page_Description.php?page=1 description of the manuscript] in the documentation of the Russian National Library.</ref>
== History of the manuscript == The manuscript was acquired by the famous [[Aleksei Musin-Pushkin|Count Musin-Pushkin]] in 1792 and subsequently presented to the [[Russian National Library]] in [[St Petersburg]] (Ms. [[#RUS-SPscMsFpIV2|F.п.IV.2]]).
